{
  "text": "The SISR method [CITATION_1] , called SRCNN 4 , is illustrated in Fig. 5 . The said work is an extension of an earlier work [CITATION_2] 5 after the introduction of larger filter sizes and additional mapping layers. The authors rely on learning directly an end-to-end mapping, between the input LR image and the corresponding HR output image, that is represented as a deep CNN. The method uses a bicubic interpolation as its pre-processing step followed by the extraction of overlapping patches, via convolution, as high dimensional vectors with as many feature maps as their dimensions. The vectors are then non-linearly mapped to each other and subsequently aggregated in the form of patches to get the reconstructed HR image that is supposed to be as close to the ground truth as possible. The authors boast results comparable to ANR [CITATION_3] and \"somehow to\" KK [CITATION_4] . However, it is reported in [CITATION_5] that on Urban100 dataset (and even with BSD100), SRCNN is outperformed by methods like Self-Ex [CITATION_6] , A+ [CITATION_7] and KK, by a fair margin. The authors of [CITATION_8] view CNN as an extension to sparse-coding-based SR methods [CITATION_9] but for the fact that the former jointly optimizes all layers unlike the segregation of components in the latter.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "6593498",
    "[CITATION_2]": "18874645",
    "[CITATION_3]": "206769988",
    "[CITATION_4]": "14925285",
    "[CITATION_5]": "8282555",
    "[CITATION_6]": "8282555",
